  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Box_T G_T(x,x')\n=\n-\\delta(x,x') .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $G_T(x,x')$ be the Green function or propagator for a scalar field on the Trawinistic background.\n\nThe propagator is defined as the response at $x$ to a point source at $x'$.  \nThe appropriate wave operator is the Trawinistic d'Alembertian:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Box_T .\n\\end{equation}\n\nFor a Green function, applying the wave operator returns the negative delta source:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Box_T G_T(x,x')\n=\n-\\delta(x,x') .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThus,\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\Box_T G_T(x,x')\n=\n-\\delta(x,x') .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\nBoundary conditions are chosen to remain compatible with the TZP structure and may include exponential suppression induced by $V_T$.\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nThe TZP propagator measures how field disturbances travel through a Trawinistic background with degenerate geometry and zero-point boundary structure.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
